## Conjecture (CPRR)
- Hypothesis: schema-shape assertions (the 4th test) catch a
  CLASS of regressions that runtime-behaviour tests can miss.
  If a future refactor drops the path property, the runtime
  test still passes for the no-arg case but the schema test
  fails immediately. Cheap insurance against silent contract
  drift.

## Validation
- The 4 tests cover the three cells of a 2x2 matrix (scoped/
  unscoped × success/error) plus the schema-shape regression
  guard. Together they pin the contract from both directions.
- Each test uses execute-tool through the public dispatcher,
  not direct internal calls, so they exercise the same path
  the model would.
- The schema test reads through tools-to-schema accessors and
  doesn't depend on JSON encoding — fast, deterministic, no
  IO.

## Refutation / known limits
- The honours path test asserts string-contains \"tests/\" is
  false. If src/sage ever contains a file named \"tests/\" (it
  doesn't and shouldn't, but theoretically), the assertion
  could false-positive. Acceptable for this codebase.
- No PBT property yet — the 4 cells are exhaustive enough that
  randomised input doesn't add coverage. A PBT property for
  the broader class \"any tool that takes a path arg honours
  scoping\" could be more valuable; filed for follow-up.
- The default-scope test is intentionally weak (just \"returns
  some result\") because the exact composition depends on
  readdir order which is non-deterministic across hosts.

## Meta - research / context / deep-dives
- Worth a future audit: every register-tool call should have
  a paired schema-shape assertion in test-tools.scm so the
  contract drift class of bug becomes a CI failure.
- Eval idea: build a synthetic model that emits valid args
  for every property declared in every tool's schema, run
  execute-tool on each, and assert no exceptions. Catches
  schema/body mismatches automatically. Would have caught
